Notation:
• List form: A = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5}
• Description: A = {even numbers less than 10}
• ∈ means 'is an element of': 3 ∈ A
• ∉ means 'is NOT an element of': 7 ∉ A

Empty Set (∅ or {}): a set with no elements. Example: {odd numbers divisible by 2}
Finite Set: has a countable number of elements. Example: {vowels} = {a, e, i, o, u}
Infinite Set: never-ending. Example: {natural numbers} = {1, 2, 3, 4, ...}
Universal Set (ξ): contains all elements under consideration.

Let A = {1, 2, 3, 4} and B = {3, 4, 5, 6}
Union: A ∪ B = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6}  (all elements, no repeats)
Intersection: A ∩ B = {3, 4}  (only elements in BOTH sets)

Universal Set ξ = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8}
A = {2, 4, 6, 8}
A' (complement of A) = {1, 3, 5, 7}  (elements in ξ but NOT in A)

Draw ξ = {1,2,3,4,5,6,7,8}, A = {1,2,3,4}, B = {3,4,5,6}
• Left circle (A only): {1, 2}
• Overlap (A ∩ B): {3, 4}
• Right circle (B only): {5, 6}
• Outside both circles: {7, 8} — these are in ξ but not in A or B
